It danced and the small child imitated him.
Je nẽ (m) të í klötiö-gẽ (_) jebi í yuliski të í mãnẽwẽ-gẽ
Later on he gave him ripe bananas
Mẽnẽũ-mĩ jamĩgweta yenã chimõli mã'-ĩte ĩã
and found something with which the dog scratched himself.
(_) Kepa jirö kwã'-ite jemẽ chichi jẽk cho-ra-mĩ
Then he gave ripe bananas to the small child.
jekepa yaba yuli ĩã í të chomõli mã'
Later on, he took out a stick and put it around his neck;
Jamĩgweta (m) yenã í të kal keyege yagã' mãgá-ite í kuli inga
And there he slipped down and came onto the water
jeska í jẽk kulijã'-wã-te í desãũ diglö inga
and crossed the river belly upwards.
A small child lied on top of his belly
e-gla (_) yaba yuli jẽk mã'ga í (_) (_) ñawa inga
and saw something like a tiger coming and climbing on a tree.
Jeska í sũã'-ite-ra nãmã bi dajũ mẽnẽga kaljula jãrga
It was going towards them on top of the branches.
(_) Je damĩũ jie-wa bata inga jie-wa kenẽga kaljula nã
Then it began to bath itself in the river
Ñerö í ñak gagá jukö diglö nã
and the small child bathed with him;
Jeska í jẽk kuliwã'ũ-te dia kenẽga wagwetaga
There, it went out on the river.
Jeska í desãũ-nẽ e-gla diglö inga
in that river the bathed once more.’
